ations are not converging to create a seamless global market. With a wealth of fresh evidence, the authors show that Japanese and German multinationals, in particular, remain only weakly committed to laissez-faire policy orientations and continue to exhibit strong allegiance to national goals in such areas as investment and employment. They also bring to light the consequences of enduring differences in government policies on, for example, industrial cartels, capital markets, and research and development. The authors agree that the world economy is becoming more complex and integrated as overt barriers to trade and investment fall away. But they conclude that the extent of this integration is decisively limited by structural divergence at the level of the firm. The book will be essential reading for those seeking to understand the growing interdependence of still-distinctive industrial societies and the wellsprings of the true global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCompetition, International. 0aInternational business enterprises. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aBaden-Württemberg.  aBank of Tokyo.  aBanyu Pharmaceuticals.  aBayerische Vereinsbank.  aDRAM memory chips.  aDaimler-Benz.  aEuropean Union.  aFederal Reserve System.  aFinanzplatz Deutschland.  aGeneral Ceramics.  aGerlach, Michael.  aHitachi.  aMitsui group.  aNew Economic Order.  aNippon Steel.  aQuandt family.  aSanwa group.  aaccounting standards.  aadministrative heritage.  aaerospace industry.  aantitrust policies.  aautomotive industry.  abiotechnology industry.  abranch banking.  acapital allocation process.  acapital mobility.  achemical industry.  achurning corporate shares.  aconstructivist theory.  acorporate nationality.  acorporatism.  acosmocorp.